name: Aardonyx
description:
Aardonyx is known from 2 immature individuals. Adults would have been much larger, probably over 10m.

Aardonyx would have been largely bipedal (walking on 2 legs) but also capable of walking on all 4 legs. This and its way of feeding are transitional features between those of basal sauropodomorphs and the more derived sauropods (large dinosaurs that walked on all fours) that came later.

name: Agilisaurus
description: Agilisaurus is known from a skull and almost complete skeleton.

name: Alamosaurus
description: This is the only Late Cretaceous sauropod that has been found in North America.

name: Albertaceratops
description: This dinosaur is known from a single, well-preserved skull from Alberta and material from a bone bed in Montana, including almost the entire skeleton, found in August 2001. It has long brow horns, unlike other members of the centrosaurine subfamily.

name: Albertosaurus
description: Albertosaurus was a close relative of Tyrannosaurus, but smaller and not as heavily built.

name: Alioramus
description: The skull of this dinosaur shows small bumps near the nose.

name: Allosaurus
description: The teeth of Allosaurus were 5-10cm long and curved backwards to prevent prey from escaping.

name: Alvarezsaurus
description: Alvarezsaurus may have been feathered.

name: Amargasaurus
description: This dinosaur had a double row of spines along its back which may have supported a twin ‘sail’ of skin. The spines on its neck vertebrae were incredibly long.

name: Ammosaurus
description: This dinosaur was very similar to Anchisaurus.

name: Ampelosaurus
description: Ampelosaurus is known from fossil teeth, postcranial bones and osteoderms ('armour plating').

name: Amygdalodon
description: Amygdalodon is known from a single partial skeleton.

name: Ankylosaurus
era: grinding teeth with a horny beak at the front
description: One of the largest armoured dinosaurus, Ankylosaurus had a wide, heavily armoured skull and a large tail club. It had a large gut space for digesting plant material.

name: Archaeopteryx
era: many small conical (cone-like) teeth in the upper jaw
description: Archaeopteryx lived at the end of the Jurassic period. By the Late Cretaceous, 70 million years later, true birds had evolved.

name: Argentinosaurus
description: The largest land animal ever found, Argentinosaurus evolved in the Cretaceous Period and belongs to a family that originated in the southern continents of Gondwana (an ancient supercontinent).

name: Arrhinoceratops
description: The only undisputed specimen of Arrhinoceratops is a skull.

name: Aucasaurus
description: Aucasaurus is known from an almost complete skeleton.

name: Austrosaurus
description: Dorsal vertebrae (part of the backbone) and limb remains of Austrosaurus have been found.

name: Bactrosaurus
description: Skull fragments and postcranial bones of at least 12 Bactrosaurus individuals, juvenile to adult, have been found.

name: Barapasaurus
description: Barapasaurus was a primitive but very large sauropod.

name: Baryonyx
description: The mouth shape of this dinosaur was very similar to that of a crocodile, and it had a large claw, about 31cm long, probably on its thumb. Baryonyx may have crouched on river banks or waded into shallow water to hook fish with its claws. It was also a scavenger.

name: Bellusaurus
description: Bellusaurus is known from 17 partial skeletons, including from young dinosaurs.

name: Borogovia
description: Only partial hindlimbs of this dinosaur have been found, so reconstructions are speculative. It was named after Lewis Carroll's borogoves from the poem Jabberwocky, published in 1871.

name: Brachiosaurus
description: Brachiosaurus held its head very high. It is likely to have eaten the leaves on tall tree-like plants.

name: Brachytrachelopan
description: Brachytrachelopan is known from partial neck and dorsal vertebrae (part of the backbone), ribs, a partial pelvis and limb bones. This dinosaur had, proportionately, the shortest neck of any known sauropod.

name: Camarasaurus
description: Camarasaurus used rows of close-set teeth to strip the leaves from trees and shrubs. Food was ground by stones in the stomach.

name: Caudipteryx
era: sharp teeth that pointed outwards, at the front of the upper jaw only
description:
This bird-like dinosaur lived after Archaeopteryx. It had a fan of feathers at the end of its tail. 

Caudipteryx has been found with gizzard stones (small stones swallowed by the dinosaur, perhaps to help digest food) and had small, weak teeth. It probably ate insects and maybe plants as well.

name: Cedarpelta
description: A skull and partial skeleton of this dinosaur have been found.

name: Centrosaurus
description: Centrosaurus had one horn on its snout and spines around the back of its neck frill.

name: Ceratosaurus
description:
Ceratosaurus means 'horned lizard'. The dinosaur was given this name because it had a row of sharp horns on its head and a row of small, bony pieces of armour running along its back. It is not known what this body armour was for, but it could have been for protection from attack by other Ceratosaurus or larger theropods such as Allosaurus and Torvosaurus.
			
				
				Scientists have estimated that Ceratosaurus was about six to seven metres long. It seems to have been quite a rare animal - remains of it are much rarer than those of the Allosaurus that lived alongside it.
			
				
				Ceratosaurus was one of the biggest hunters in the Jurassic Period. Its prey probably included plant-eating dinosaurs, but some scientists have suggested that it may have fed upon aquatic animals such as fish, turtles and crocodiles.
			
				
				Ceratosaurus is remarkable for the very long, slender teeth in its upper jaw. These teeth could be over nine centimetres long, nearly as long as the lower jaw was deep, so they would almost stick out beyond it when the mouth was closed. Nobody really knows why the teeth were so long, but they may have helped it inflict deep, slashing wounds in prey.

name: Chaoyangsaurus
description: Chaoyangsaurus is the earliest known ceratopsian (shield dinosaur).

name: Chasmosaurus
description: Chasmosaurus had a small nose horn, blunt brow horns and a long neck frill with holes.

name: Chindesaurus
description: Chindesaurus had a long whip-like tail and long legs. No skull has been found, so its reconstruction is guesswork based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Chinshakiangosaurus
description: Chinshakiangosaurus is only known from a fragmentary skeleton.

name: Chungkingosaurus
description: This dinosaur is known from a partial skull and a partial skeleton.

name: Coelophysis
description:
Early carnivores
				In the Late Triassic Period dinosaurs were not at the top of the food chain. Instead, early large reptiles called phytosaurs and rauisuchids domintated.

Early meat-eating dinosaurs like Coelophysis relied on their speed and agility to catch a variety of animals like insects and small reptiles. The sharp teeth and grasping claws of Coelophysis would have helped them to hold and kill their food.
			
				Cannibalism?
				A fossil find of an adult skeleton with what appeared to be young Coelophysis bones inside its rib cage led scientists to speculate that Coelophysis ate each other when the opportunity arose.

Recent analysis has disproved this, however, by showing that the bones inside the ribcage are not a baby Coelophysis after all, but belong to a small crocodile.
			
				Hollow bones
				Coelophysis means 'hollow form' and this comes from the hollow limb bones. This feature was shared by many other dinosaurs, and would have given Coelophysis a lightly-built body, helping it to be a swift, agile hunter.

name: Conchoraptor
description: Remains of this dinosaur have been found with feathers preserved. Sexual differences can be seen in the plumage.

name: Cryolophosaurus
description: Cryolophosaurus is one of the earliest meat-eating dinosaurs found so far. It lived in what is now Antarctica and had a small curved crest on the top of its head.

name: Dacentrurus
description: Dacentrurus was the first stegosaur ever discovered.

name: Deinocheirus
description: Originally, scientists only had a pair of arm bones with big, long claws to learn about Deinocheirus. But in 2014, new material revealed that it had a unique, large hump on its back, supported by its back bones. Now we know that it was a truly bizarre-looking creature, with huge, clawed hands, a beaked head like a duck and a hump like a camel.

name: Deinonychus
description: Deinonychus could hold onto its prey with fearsome front claws. One huge claw on each foot swivelled - a kick would rip prey apart. When not in use the claw was held out of the way to keep it sharp. Deinonychus may have hunted Tenontosaurus.

name: Deltadromeus
description: Deltadromeus is known from a single partial skeleton.

name: Dicraeosaurus
description: This dinosaur is named 'forked lizard' because of the forked spines in its backbone.

name: Dilophosaurus
era: lots of sharp and curved teeth
description: Dilophosaurus was a fast-moving meat-eating dinosaur. A kink in its upper jaw may mean that it ate a certain kind of food, or attacked by gripping and holding on to prey – modern crocodiles have a similar kink. The pair of thin bony crests on its head may have been for display.

name: Diplodocus
era: rows of teeth like a comb
description:
Diplodocus had a long neck that it would have used to reach high and low vegetation, and to drink water. There has been some debate over how such a long neck would have been held.
 
Scientists now think that ligaments running from the hip to the back of the neck would have allowed Diplodocus to hold its neck in a horizontal position without using muscles. The vertebrae (back bones) are split down the middle and this space could have held ligaments like these.
 
Diplodocus may have had narrow, pointed bony spines lining its back.
			
				A Museum icon
				In 1905 a cast of a Diplodocus skeleton was donated to the Museum by the wealthy businessman Andrew Carnegie, based on the original specimen in the Carnegie Museum in the USA.

King Edward VII had requested a copy of the newly discovered dinosaur after seeing a picture of it in Carnegie's Scottish castle. From 1979 to early 2017 the cast - known affectionately as Dippy - was on display in the Museum's Hintze Hall.

In 1993, Dippy's tail was lifted from the ground after research revealed that Diplodocus tails would have been raised high to balance the neck.
 
Every two years or so, Museum experts used specialist equipment to clean the 292 bones that make up Dippy. It takes two staff two days to clean the cast and make sure it is maintained for future generations to enjoy.

Dippy has now left the Museum to go on a natural history adventure. From February 2018 to October 2021 Dippy will be visiting eight venues across the UK.

name: Dromaeosaurus
description: The back foot of this dinosaur had a large claw for kicking.

name: Dromiceiomimus
description: Dromiceiomimus looked very like a modern ostrich, but without the thick layer of feathers (it may have had some feathers). Dromiceiomimus is now a nomen dubium (dubious name), because the fossils are no longer thought to represent a distinct dinosaur type.

name: Dubreuillosaurus
description: Partial skull and partial skeletons of Dubreuillosaurus have been found, but not enough to work out its overall size, although we know it was a large dinosaur.

name: Edmontosaurus
era: horny beak and 1,000 grinding cheek teeth
description: Hard conifer needles, twigs and seeeds have been found in Edmontosaurus stomachs. Mummified specimens have some preserved skin, so we know its texture (but not the colour).

name: Einiosaurus
description: Einiosaurus had a large downward-curving nasal horn.

name: Eolambia
description: Eolambia is known from the skulls and postcrania of several individuals, both juveniles and adults.

name: Eotyrannus
description: Eotyrannus is known from a partial skull and partial skeleton.

name: Equijubus
description: Known from skull and postcrania, Equijubus is thought to be the earliest duck-billed dinosaur (hadrosaur).

name: Erketu
description: Erketu is known from articulated cervical vertebrae (backbone), a sternal plate (breastbone) and an articulated lower leg.

name: Erlikosaurus
description: Erlikosaurus is known from a skull and partial skeleton.

name: Euhelopus
description: Euhelopus is known from a skull and partial postcranial skeletons.

name: Euoplocephalus
description: Euoplocephalus had bony spikes and armour plating on its back, and a bony tail club used for defence.

name: Europasaurus
description: Although Europasaurus was a dwarf sauropod, it still grew to around 6m long.

name: Fukuisaurus
description: Fukuisaurus is only known from a skull, so the rest of the reconstruction is guesswork based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Gargoyleosaurus
description: Gargoyleosaurus is known from a skull and partial postcranium, which was found partially articulated (the bones were joined as they would have been when the dinosaur was alive).

name: Gastonia
description: Gastonia is known from a skull and the partial skeletons of several individuals.

name: Giganotosaurus
era: long, blade-like and serrated - ideal for slicing
description: Giganotosaurus is known from very fragmentary remains. Taller and longer but slimmer than Tyrannosaurus rex, Giganotosaurus lived millions of years earlier and in South America not North America.Giganotosaurus had 3 fingers on its hands, not 2 like T.rex. It may have hunted Argentinosaurus.

name: Giraffatitan
description: Considered to be distinct from Brachiosaurus by some scientists, Giraffatitan is known from the fossils of several individuals.

name: Gobisaurus
description: Gobisaurus is known from a skull and postcranium. The size of the skull suggests that the dinosaur was up to 5m long.

name: Gorgosaurus
description: Gorgosaurus is known from at least 12 complete or almost complete skulls and several partial skeletons.

name: Graciliceratops
description: A partial skull and skeleton of Graciliceratops have been found. This was a tiny dinosaur, it may have only been 80cm long.

name: Gryposaurus
description: Gryposaurus is known from several skeletons, including one which is fully articulated (the bones were joined as they would have been when the dinosaur was alive).

name: Guaibasaurus
description: This early dinosaur is known from a partial skeleton. Scientists are not sure how it relates to later dinosaurs.

name: Guanlong
description: Guanlong had an air-filled crest on its head. It is the earliest known tyrannosauroid (Tyrannosaurus-like) dinosaur.

name: Hadrosaurus
description: Hadrosaurus is now a nomen dubium (dubious name), because the fossils are no longer thought to represent a distinct dinosaur type.

name: Hagryphus
description: Hagryphus is known from only a left hand, fragmentary metatarsals and pedal phalanges (part of a foot), so this reconstruction is based on these and Chirostenotes, a very similar dinosaur.

name: Haplocanthosaurus
description: Haplocanthosaurus is known from partial skeletons that lack skulls, so the shape of the head in reconstructions is based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Harpymimus
description: A skull and partial skeleton of Harpymimus have been found. This dinosaur had small, blunt teeth.

name: Hesperosaurus
description: Hesperosaurus is known from a complete skeleton and a skull.

name: Heyuannia
description: Ingenia is known from a skull and partial skeleton.

name: Homalocephale
description: Homalocephale is known from a complete skull and a nearly complete postcranium.

name: Hylaeosaurus
description: A specimen of Hylaeosaurus was one of the 3 fossils first identified as dinosaurs by Richard Owen in 1841.

name: Hypacrosaurus
description: Complete Hypacrosaurus skeletons have been found, from embryos to adults.

name: Iguanodon
era: chewing cheek teeth and horny beak
description: Iguanodon could probably walk on all fours or on two legs. It had a large thumb spike on the end of its hand, probably to fend-off predators, and the structure of the muscles inside its head suggest it had a very long tongue.

name: Indosuchus
description: An almost complete skeleton of Indosuchus has been found.

name: Irritator
description:
Irritator was quite like Spinosaurus. It is known only from a skull, so the sail is a guess.

The type species, Irritator challengeri was named after Professor Challenger from Arthur Conan Doyle's novel 'The Lost World', published in 1912.

name: Isisaurus
description: This dinosaur is the one most similar to modern-day giraffes. Fungus has been found in its poo!

name: Jaxartosaurus
description: Jaxartosaurus is known only from a skull roof and braincase.

name: Jingshanosaurus
description: A complete skeleton and skull of Jingshanosaurus have been found. It was one of the last prosauropods.

name: Jinzhousaurus
description: An almost complete skull and some postcranial remains of this dinosaur have been found.

name: Jobaria
description: Jobaria is known from a skull and several skeletons.

name: Juravenator
description: Juravenator was the second non-avian (not bird-like) theropod (small meat-eating dinosaur) to be found in the region of Solnhofen. The type specimen shows impressions of scaly skin along the tail.

name: Khaan
description: This dinosaur is known from 3 skeletons with skulls. It is a beaked dinosaur very similar to Oviraptor, Ingenia and Conchoraptor.

name: Kotasaurus
description: Kotasaurus is known from a nearly complete skeleton that lacks the skull, so the reconstruction uses guesswork based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Lapparentosaurus
description: Lapparentosaurus is known from partial skeletons lacking skulls, so reconstructions involve guesswork based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Lesothosaurus
description: This dinosaur was small and agile and had 5 fingers on each 'hand', although these were probably not well adapted for grasping.

name: Liaoceratops
description: Two almost complete Liaoceratops skulls have been found.

name: Ligabuesaurus
description: Ligabuesaurus is known from fragmentary remains, including a maxilla (jawbone) with teeth, 6 cervical and dorsal vertebrae (part of the backbone), and girdle and limb bones.

name: Lophorhothon
description: A disarticulated skull and skeleton belonging to Lophorhothon have been found.

name: Lophostropheus
description: Our knowledge of Lophostropheus is based on a tooth, vertebrae and part of a pelvis.

name: Lurdusaurus
description: Lurdusaurus is known from a partial skull and postcranium.

name: Majungasaurus
description: Majungasaurus is known from a complete skull and partial skeletons.

name: Malawisaurus
description: Skull elements, teeth, vertebrae, limb bones and osteoderms (armour) of several individuals have been found.

name: Mapusaurus
description: This dinosaur may have hunted in packs and lived in family groups. Mapusaurus may have been larger than Giganotosaurus, making it the largest meat eating dinosaur found so far.

name: Marshosaurus
description: Marshosaurus is known from a partial skull and postcranium.

name: Maxakalisaurus
description: Maxakalisaurus is known from a partial skeleton, including some skull fragments and osteoderms (large skin adornments). Its teeth were ridged, unusual for sauropods. Some of the bones bear teeth marks, suggesting scavenging activity.

name: Megalosaurus
description: Megalosaurus was one of the first dinosaurs discovered.

name: Melanorosaurus
description: Melanorosaurus is a very early sauropod.

name: Metriacanthosaurus
description: Metriacanthosaurus is known only from a partial postcranial skeleton, so reconstructions are guesswork based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Microceratus
description: Microceratops is a nomen dubium (dubious name) - it is no longer considered a distinct dinosaur group. The only specimen is of a young dinosaur so we do not know how large the adults grew.

name: Microraptor
description: A feathered dinosaur. One species, Microraptor gui had long flight feathers on all 4 limbs. It may have been capable of guided flight.

name: Minmi
description: This dinosaur is known from an almost complete skeleton with armour in place.

name: Monolophosaurus
description: Monolophosaurus had a long bony crest on its head, perhaps for display.

name: Mononykus
description: Mononykus is known from partial skeletons.

name: Nanshiungosaurus
description: Only the vertebral column and pelvis of Nanshiungosaurus have been found, no skull. So the shape of the head in reconstructions is based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Nemegtosaurus
description: Nemegtosaurus is only known from a skull and mandible (lower jawbone), so reconstructions are speculative.

name: Neovenator
description: Neovenator is known from a partial skull and skeleton.

name: Neuquenosaurus
description: Neuquenosaurus is known from dorsal vertebrae (part of the backbone), most of the tail, a complete pelvis, limb bones and osteoderms (hardened, bone-like, raised scales on its back).

name: Nigersaurus
description: A partial Nigersaurus skull and numerous postcranial bones have been found.

name: Nipponosaurus
description: Our knowledge of Nipponosaurus is based on a partial skull and postcranial of a juvenile.

name: Noasaurus
description: A skull and some postcranial remains of Noasaurus have been found.

name: Nomingia
description: Nomingia is known from a partial postcranium. The skull has not been found, so this is reconstructed from similar dinosaurs.

name: Nothronychus
description: A partial skull and postcranium of Nothronychus have been found. This odd dinosaur may even have evolved from a carnivore to a herbivore.

name: Nqwebasaurus
description: Nqwebasaurus is known from a partial skeleton lacking the skull, so the shape of the head is based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Opisthocoelicaudia
description: Opisthocoelicaudia is known from a skeleton that lacks the skull and neck, so their reconstruction is based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Oryctodromeus
description:
Remains of this dinosaur were found in its burrow, along with the remains of 2 juveniles. The burrow was around 30cm wide and 70cm long.
 The holotype adult specimen (the specimen that was first used to describe the species) consists of skull bones, vertebrae, ribs, scapulocoracoid, humerus, ulna, radius, tibiae, partial fibula, and a metatarsal.

name: Othnielia
description: Only partial skeletons of Othnielia have been found.

name: Oviraptor
description: The curved upper and lower jaws of Oviraptor would have been able to crush even hard objects. This dinosaur may have eaten eggs, or fed on fish and shellfish.

name: Pantydraco
description: Knowledge about Pantydraco is based on a partial juvenile skeleton which was previously thought to be a Thecodontosaurus.

name: Paralititan
description: A partial postcranial skeleton of Paralititan has been found, but no skull, so reconstructions of the shape of the head are based on similar dinosaurs. The remains were found in a fossil mangrove swamp.

name: Patagosaurus
description: Many Patagosaurus skeletons have been found.

name: Pelicanimimus
description: Pelicanimimus had more than 200 very small fine teeth. The holotype (the defining fossil of this dinosaur) is well preserved, with a visible throat pouch.

name: Pentaceratops
description: This dinosaur had a very large skull, almost 3m long.

name: Pinacosaurus
description: Groups of young Pinacosaurus dinosaurs have been found fossilised together.

name: Plateosaurus
era: grinding teeth with a horny beak at the front
description: Plateosaurus had 5-fingered hands and a large thumb claw, which may have been for defence or for collecting food. Finds in Germany suggest that this dinosaur may have lived in herds.

name: Poekilopleuron
description: Only a partial Poekilopleuron skeleton has been found.

name: Proceratosaurus
description: Proceratosaurus is known only from a partial skull, so reconstructions are speculative.

name: Procompsognathus
description: Procompsognathus was similar to Ornitholestes. The only specimen is badly crushed.

name: Prosaurolophus
description: Prosaurolophus is known from the skeletons of 24-29 individuals, some articulated (the bones were joined as they would have been in life).

name: Protoceratops
era: shearing and grinding teeth with a horny beak at the front
description: One Protoceratops specimen was fossilised while being attacked by Velociraptor.

name: Protohadros
description: Partial skull and postcranial remains of Protohadros have been found. This was a very early duck-billed dinosaur (hadrosaur).

name: Quaesitosaurus
description: Scientists are not very sure of the adult length of this dinosaur. Dates are also uncertain - Quaesitosaurus may have lived 84-71 million years ago.

name: Rebbachisaurus
description: Rebbachisaurus is known only from dorsal vertebrae (part of the backbone), scapula, humerus and sacrum, so reconstructions are quite speculative. But we know it had large spines on its backbone which could have supported a 'sail'.

name: Rhoetosaurus
description: Only a partial skeleton of Rhoetosaurus has been found.

name: Rinchenia
description: Rinchenia is known from a skull and fragmentary postcrania, so reconstructions are quite speculative, based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Riojasaurus
description: 20 Riojasaurus skeletons have been found, both adult and young.

name: Rugops
description: Rugops is known from an almost complete skull. The skull is relatively delicate, suggesting that this was a scavenger, not an attacking dinosaur like Tyrannosaurus. Rows of holes in the skull may indicate that it had a crest of some kind.

name: Saltasaurus
description:
Fossils have been found showing that Saltasaurus had small bony nodules embedded in its skin, finally confirming that one a least one group of sauropods, called titanosaurs, had armour plates.
Saltasaurus is one of the last sauropods, living just before the group's extinction.

name: Saltopus
description: Saltopus was a small dinosaur. It was probably under 1m when fully grown, but we are not exactly sure as only a fragmentary skeleton has been found.

name: Sarcosaurus
description: A partial pelvis (hip), femur and vertebrae (backbone) belonging to Sarcosaurus have been found.

name: Sauropelta
description: Sauropelta had large shoulder spines.

name: Secernosaurus
description: Secernosaurus was the first hadrosaurid to be found in South America.

name: Segisaurus
description: Segisaurus is known only from a partial postcranial skeleton. No full adult has been found, but this was a small carnivorous dinosaur and probably ate insects.

name: Shamosaurus
description: A skull and partial skeleton of Shamosaurus have been found, but not enough to estimate its full length.

name: Shanag
description: Shanag is known only from skull fragments.

name: Shuvuuia
description: Shuvuuia is known from a well-preserved skull and postcranium. This very small desert dinosaur may have eaten termites. Its lower jaw was not interlocked with the skull, allowing its mouth to open very wide for larger prey.

name: Silvisaurus
description: Silvisaurus is known from a skull and fragmentary postcrania, so reconstructions are mostly guesswork based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Sinocalliopteryx
description: Sinocalliopteryx is known from a complete skeleton with preserved filamentous integumentary structures (hair-like 'protofeathers'). Part of the leg of a dromaeosaurid (a small, fast-moving dinosaur that walked on 2 legs) and also some gastroliths (stomach stones) were found in its abdomen.

name: Sinosauropteryx
description: Sinosauropteryx had feathery wing-like structures, but could not fly.

name: Sinovenator
description: A partial skeleton and skulls of Sinvenator have been found.

name: Sinraptor
description: Almost complete skeletons of Sinraptor have been found.

name: Spinosaurus
description: Spinosaurus is only known from fragmentary remains. Size estimates range up to 18m, which would make it the longest meat eater, although more slender than T. rex or Giganotosaurus.

name: Staurikosaurus
description: Staurikosaurus was one of the earliest dinosaurs.

name: Stegosaurus
description:
A large, slow moving plant-eater, Stegosaurus would have defended itself from predators like Allosaurus and Ceratosaurus with its powerful spiked tail.
 
The bony plates along its back were embedded in the skin of the animal, not attached to its skeleton, which is why in most fossil finds the plates are separated from the body.

When O C Marsh described the first fossil of a Stegosaurus, he concluded that the plates would have lain flat on its back. After finding a specimen that had been covered with mud, which had held the plates in place, Marsh realised that they stood vertically, alternately on either side of the spine.

Scientists are not exactly sure what the plates were used for. They may have warned off predators, or allowed members of the same species to recognise each other. Another suggestion is that the plates were used to regulate body temperature.

There are tiny grooves in the plate surfaces, possibly where blood vessels would have been. The amount of blood passing through these vessels would determine the amount of heat transfer.

Compared with the rest of its body, Stegosaurus had a small head and its brain was around the size of a plum!
			
				A new star specimen
				The most complete Stegosaurus skeleton ever found went on display in the Museum’s Earth Hall in December 2014.

Identified as a member of the species Stegosaurus stenops, this spectacular specimen is helping researchers gain new insights into what Stegosaurus would have looked like when it was alive, as well as how it walked, ate and behaved.

name: Stenopelix
description: Stenopelix is only known from a fragmentary specimen.

name: Struthiomimus
description: Struthiomimus looked a bit like a featherless ostrich with a long tail.

name: Struthiosaurus
description: Struthiosaurus may have been a dwarf ankylosaur, living on islands.

name: Suchomimus
copyright: © Andrey Atuchin© The Paleoart of Julius Csotonyi published by Titan Books
description: This dinosaur is similar to Spinosaurus and Baryonyx.

name: Supersaurus
description: Known only from certain bones, including vertebrae (backbones).

name: Talarurus
description: Talarurus is known from fairly complete skeletons.

name: Tanius
description: Both skull and postcranial material has been found for this dinosaur.

name: Tarbosaurus
description: Tarbosaurus is very like Tyrannosaurus.

name: Tarchia
description: Tarchia is known from a complete skeleton, including an armoured skull, and is the largest and most recent anylosaur. Tarchia lived in the desert.

name: Telmatosaurus
description: Telmatosaurus is known from fragmentary remains.

name: Thecodontosaurus
description: The original material used to describe Thecodontosaurus has been lost, but several other specimens are known.

name: Therizinosaurus
description: This large dinosaur is only known from the forelimb skeleton, so reconstructions are mostly guesswork.

name: Torosaurus
description: This dinosaur may have lived in social groups. It has the largest display crest of any ceratopsian and, like all the others, had a 'beak' for grazing.

name: Triceratops
description:
With its 3 horns, a parrot-like beak and a large frill that could reach nearly 1 metre (3 feet) across, the Triceratops skull is one of the largest and most striking of any land animal.

The horns could have been used to fend off attacks from Tyrannosaurus. A partial Triceratops fossil collected in 1997 has a horn that was bitten off, with bite marks that match Tyrannosaurus. The fossil shows that the horn healed after being bitten, so at least some Triceratops survived these encounters.

Puncture marks on fossil frills show that male Triceratops also used their horns to fight each other, probably to impress females.
			
				Herd instinct
				Many other horned dinosaurs are known to have lived in herds because of a fossil find of many different individuals at the same location.

By moving in herds, prey animals can warn each other of danger and lessen their chances of being singled out by a predator.

However, Triceratops was unusual in this respect, as their remains are usually found individually, suggesting they may have spent much of their lives alone.
			
				Why the frill?
				The Triceratops frill might have helped to protect its neck, but some specimens show Tyrannosaurus bite marks puncturing the frill, so it wasn't always enough.

The frills could also have been used to attract mates, as a way for members of the same species to recognise each other.

name: Tsagantegia
description: Only the skull of Tsagantegia has been found, so the rest is guesswork based on similar dinosaurs.

name: Tsintaosaurus
description: Tsintaosaurus is known from skulls and a partial skeleton.

name: Tylocephale
description: Tylocephale is known from a partial skull, including the mandible (jawbone).

name: Tyrannosaurus
description:
The ultimate carnivore
				Tyrannosaurus lives up to its reputation as one of the most fearsome animals of all time. Its powerful jaws had 60 teeth, each one up to 20cm (8 inches) long and its bite was around 3 times as powerful than that of a lion.
 
Bite marks found on Triceratops and Edmontosaurus fossil bones show that Tyrannosaurus could crunch through bone. Analysis of fossilised Tyrannosaurus dung show that it contained the bones of its prey. 
			
				Hunter or scavenger?
				The Tyrannosaurus skull was over 1.5m (5 feet) long and the cavity that housed the part of the brain responsible for smell was relatively large.

Tyrannosaurus would have used its good sense of smell to hunt live prey and locate dead bodies to scavenge. It would have been able to scare off any other scavengers, so it didn't have to share.
			
				Lone or pack hunter?
				Some Tyrannosaurus fossils show bite marks from other tyrannosaurs, so it's clear that they fought each other, whether over food or mates.

We know that close relatives of Tyrannosaurus sometimes lived together because there are fossils of groups who were buried together, but we don't know for sure if they hunted alone, or in packs like lions and wolves do today. So far, no groups of Tyrannosaurus skeletons have been found.

name: Udanoceratops
description: Udanoceratops is known from a partial skull and postcranial skeleton. This 'ceratops' had hardly any head frill.

name: Unenlagia
description: Unenlagia is known from postcranial remains. The shoulder joint indicates a wide range of arm movements could be made. This may even have evolved from flying ancestors.

name: Urbacodon
description: Urbacodon is known only from a left dentary (the bone of the lower jaw that bears the teeth), which contained 32 unserrated teeth. Its name comes from 'URBAC', the acronym for international joint expeditions to the Kyzylkum Desert.

name: Utahraptor
copyright: © The Paleoart of Julius Csotonyi published by Titan Books
description: Utahraptor is similar to Velociraptor, but much larger.

name: Valdosaurus
description: Valdosaurus is known from postcranial bones, teeth and dentary (the lower jaw bone that bears the teeth).

name: Velociraptor
description:
As portrayed in the Jurassic Park movies,Velociraptor was recreated at twice its actual size and closely modelled on Deinonychus. Though this was seen as unscientific at the time, soon after the first film was released, a dinosaur of the same type, Utahraptor, was discovered, even larger than the virtual Velociraptors. 
Velociraptor is now thought to have had a fine feather-like covering.

name: Yimenosaurus
description: Quite a lot is known about this dinosaur from 10 partial skeletons and a skull.

name: Yingshanosaurus
description: This dinosaur was named in a Japanese dinosaur book, but has not been fully described yet (it is a nomen nudum).

name: Yinlong
description: The earliest known ceratopsian, showing features of ceratopsians, pachycephalosaurians and heterodontosaurids.

name: Yuanmousaurus
description: Yuanmousaurus is known from an incomplete skeleton.

name: Yunnanosaurus
description: 20 Yunnanosaurus skeletons have been found, including adult and juvenile specimens.
